{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508527"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:06:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:06:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2768"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2768"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.17,0.13,0.57,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2768"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99806"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2768"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2768"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82191"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"480"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3655"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3671"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16025"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99806"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old man is due to have elective knee surgery for repair of his anterior cruciate ligament. He has been taking aspirin intermittently for pain relief.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe surgeon advises him to stop taking aspirin prior to the surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate minimum timeframe this patient should stop taking aspirin?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["2 days","3 days","24 hours","7 days","14 days"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAspirin (acetylsalicylic acid) irreversibly inhibits the cyclooxygenase-1 (COX-1) enzyme in platelets. This exerts an anti-thrombotic effect by preventing the formation of thromboxane A2 (TXA-2), which is a potent platelet activator. Because platelets do not have a nucleus, they are unable to produce new protein and therefore replace the inhibited COX-1 molecules, and thus the anti-thrombotic effect of aspirin lasts for the lifespan of the platelet i.e., \u003Cstrong\u003E7 - 10 days\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst guidelines may differ slightly between institutions, a standard recommendation is to withhold aspirin for at least this duration before surgery to allow the inhibited platelets to be turned over. The other durations offered are either too short (ie \u003Cstrong\u003E24hrs, 2 days\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003E3 days\u003C/strong\u003E) or unnecessarily long (\u003Cstrong\u003E14 days\u003C/strong\u003E) compared to this timeframe, making 7 days the most appropriate answer. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInhibited platelets during surgery increase the risk of bleeding, and this can be mitigated by ceasing aspirin prior to the operation. Whether or not the aspirin should be held is a matter of balancing surgical bleeding risk against the strength of the indication for aspirin. Given that this patient is taking aspirin purely as analgesia (compared to, for example, a cardiac indication) makes the decision clearer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aspirin may increase surgical bleeding risk, and if deemed appropriate, held for at least 7 days prior to surgery."],"references":["Paez Espinosa EV, Murad JP, Khasawneh FT. Aspirin: pharmacology and clinical applications. Thrombosis. 2012;2012:173124."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82191"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2768"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82191"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-22T11:21:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-22T11:21:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2768"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99806"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/480"},"attributes":{"emoji":